  <h2>Maryland's Equitable Distribution Standard</h2>
  <p>
    Maryland is an <strong>equitable distribution</strong> state — meaning that marital property is divided fairly but not necessarily equally. Courts have broad discretion in determining what constitutes a fair division based on a range of statutory factors set forth in Maryland Family Law Article § 8-205, including:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The contributions — both monetary and non-monetary — of each spouse to the marriage</li>
    <li>The value of each spouse's property interests</li>
    <li>The economic circumstances of each spouse at the time of the award</li>
    <li>The duration of the marriage</li>
    <li>The ages and physical and mental conditions of each party</li>
    <li>How and when specific property was acquired</li>
    <li>Each party's contribution to the acquisition, maintenance, or depreciation of property</li>
    <li>Dissipation (wasteful spending or intentional depletion) of marital property</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <h3 style="margin-top:0; color:#0D6E6E;">Marital vs. Non-Marital Property</h3>
    <p>Not all property is subject to division. <strong>Marital property</strong> includes assets acquired by either spouse during the marriage. <strong>Non-marital (separate) property</strong> — such as gifts, inheritances, and assets owned before marriage — is generally protected. However, commingling can blur these boundaries. Our attorneys conduct thorough tracing analysis to properly classify your assets.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Types of Assets We Handle</h2>

  <h3>Real Estate & Family Home</h3>
  <p>
    The marital home is often the most significant asset in a divorce. Options include selling the home and splitting proceeds, one spouse buying out the other, or deferred sale arrangements (often used when minor children are involved). Our attorneys help you evaluate which approach best serves your financial and family goals.
  </p>

  <h3>Retirement Accounts & Pensions</h3>
  <p>
    Retirement accounts — including 401(k)s, IRAs, 403(b)s, and defined benefit pension plans — accrued during the marriage are generally marital property. Dividing retirement accounts requires a <strong>Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO)</strong>, which our attorneys are experienced in drafting and implementing without triggering tax penalties.
  </p>

  <h3>Investment Accounts & Financial Assets</h3>
  <p>
    Stocks, bonds, mutual funds, brokerage accounts, and other financial instruments accumulated during the marriage are subject to division. Our attorneys work with financial analysts to accurately value these assets and develop equitable distribution proposals.
  </p>

  <h3>Business Interests</h3>
  <p>
    If either spouse owns a business or business interest, valuation and division become particularly complex. We coordinate with forensic accountants and business valuation experts to ensure accurate assessment and fair division. For detailed information on business divorce matters, see our <a href="/divorces-involving-businesses" class="text-teal font-semibold hover:text-teal-600">Divorces Involving Businesses</a> page.
  </p>

  <h3>Vehicles, Personal Property & Collectibles</h3>
  <p>
    Vehicles, artwork, jewelry, antiques, and personal property also require valuation and distribution. Our attorneys ensure these items are properly inventoried and fairly addressed in your divorce settlement.
  </p>

  <h3>Debt Allocation</h3>
  <p>
    Marital debt — mortgages, credit cards, car loans, and other obligations accumulated during the marriage — must also be divided. Our attorneys work to ensure you are not unfairly burdened with debt that should be your spouse's responsibility.
  </p>

  <h2>Dissipation of Marital Assets</h2>
  <p>
    If your spouse has been wasting, hiding, or purposefully depleting marital assets — whether through reckless spending, undisclosed accounts, or fraudulent transfers — our attorneys know how to uncover dissipation and seek appropriate remedies from the court. We work with forensic financial experts when necessary to trace assets and protect your interests.
  </p>

